The "unmistakeable" l=
ink to the *physical* evolution of life on earth does not imply an increasi=
ng sequence of *spiritual* perfection, as you cannot directly map the physi=
cal to the spiritual. More importantly, if your understanding is correct, w=
hy isn't perfection occurring in the FINAL incarnation but occurring well b=
efore?
=A0
*=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *
=A0
First, regar=
ding Krishna being a "poornavatara", SrimadBhagavatam (SB) does not say tha=
t Rama is not one. In fact, Parasara, father of Vyasa, explicitly mentioned=
 that Rama, Krishna, Narasimha and Varaha are "poornavataras"
 (used that e=
xact expression) while other avataras have some amount of jivatmamsa too (t=
hough paramatmamsa dominates jivatmamsa).
=A0
Secondly, after describing th=
e avataras, SB says that there are in fact innumerable avataras and that al=
l rishis, munis, manus, demigods etc are avataras of Supreme Lord. It is un=
der THAT context that 1.3.28 then proceeds to say "these avataras are parti=
al, while Krishna is Lord Himself." I question if the deduction that Krishn=
a *alone* is Lord Himself and Rama is not is accurate! It only seems to say=
 that all these rishis, manus, demigods etc are partial. As I said above, P=
ararsara explicitly said that both Rama and Krishna are poornavataras.
=A0
=
Third, let us ask a very fundamental question: What exactly does it mean if=
 an avatara is "Lord Himself"?
=A0
*=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=
=A0=A0 *
=A0
While SB talks of Krishna being "Lord Himself" in 1.3.28, it a=
lso says in 1.3.30: "forms of Supreme Lord, who is in
 reality formless (ar=
Upa) and of the nature of pure consciousness (chidAtman), are manufactured =
by the qualities of Maya". In the next verse, it further compares forms of =
Lord to clouds in sky and dirt in air. Just as sky *contains* clouds and is=
 beyond them, similarly Lord *contains* forms and is beyond them. So, again=
, what is the meaning of a specific form that descended on earth being "Lor=
d Himself"? I am afraid people may be misinterpreting this notion based on =
their fancies and conditioning..
=A0
All beings are made up of paramatma (s=
upreme/absolute being) and jivatma (living/relative being). The latter port=
ion is dominant in us and is responsible for desires and rebirth. Great ava=
taras descend from a higher portion of paramatma. Very rarely avataras desc=
end entirely from paramatma without ANY jivatma portion. Rama and Krishna a=
re specific examples given by Parasara.
=A0
They are entirely divine, but t=
hey do not encapsulate the entire divinity!!!! After all,
 "entire divinity=
" cannot be encapsulated by any form just as no cloud can contain the entir=
e sky. They take part in the drama obeying and executing the divine will bu=
t NOT altering it. This applies to Krishna as well as Rama.
=A0
*=A0=A0=A0=
=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *
