spassionate manner, that he killed Ravana not to rescue her, but it was the=
 Dharma to do so, and to unhold his family honour. That too was the dharma =
of that age when he lived, family honor. The way I look at this grand epic,=
 and I bow humbly to the genius of Rishis Valmiki for representing the thin=
gs as they are, as a scribe, as a poet, as an observer, and not adding his =
own preferences to it anywhere, in the 14 years of tribulation that Rama fa=
ced which culminated into his killing Ravana, he changed into the most disp=
assionate leader, such that no personal consideration or emotions or passio=
ns can overturn the Rajadharma. His life is a lesson of what a true leader =
must be!<br><br>Krshna, OTOH, had this immaculate detachment right from bir=
th. I am not taking his  supernatural feats into account. It is his si=
ngular and constant detachment from situations, from people, from environme=
nt,
 from circumstances that mark his life. At the age of eight, he decides=
 to leave Vrindavana for Mathura. All his friends, his foster parents, his =
village-folks who so loved him, pleaded with him that it would make no sens=
e for him to leave the shelter, love and comfort of his happy, settled vill=
age life and head into an unknown destiny and destination. Krshna tried to =
reason with them, then he understood that they won't understand, he promise=
d he will return back once his work in Mathura is over. He never returned. =
Later, much later, when the Gopis came to him asking him to participate in =
their dance, he obliged. But the moment some of them started getting jealou=
s and possessive of Krshna, he removed himself quietly from the scene, sayi=
ng that he belongs to everyone equally and no one has any special right ove=
r him. When Shishupala abused Krshna, the later merely kept dropping flower=
s on the floor, smiling and counting. The moment the 100th abuse was
 over,=
 he swiftly cut off Shishupala's head and was back into his poise. But when=
 Bhurishrava unfairly accused Krshna of being a revolutionist and charlatan=
, Krshna did not kill him. When Duryodhana, who used to think of Krshna as =
another black magician, wanted to arrest him, Krshna showed his vikarala ro=
opa in the assembly of kings, yet he did not finish the enemies off. The ve=
ry next moment he was back into his own poised self. Never in the whole Mah=
abharata is there one instance of his going overboard, never a single shade=
 of depression, equivocation, or lack of confidence in his actions, irrespe=
ctive of what others say or think of him. And then right in the middle of t=
he greatest war he had the perfect equipoise to deliver the most sublime sp=
iritual philosophy. That is why his life remains the best ideal of Karma-Yo=
ga. For a true Karma-Yogi by definition can never be dejected. It is imposs=
ible. Neither the action nor the results belong to the
 instrument. When ru=
nning away from the battle-field and killing Kaliya Yavana, or when advisin=
g Bheema to tear apart Jarashanda, or gesturing Bheema to hit Duryodhana be=
low the waist, or getting Shikhandi to face Bhisma, Krshna, as if by some D=
ivine Intuition, knew exactly how the situations must be lined up which wou=
ld cause the destruction of these people. This kind of knowledge cannot com=
e by the rational thinking. But happens when one is constantly and consciou=
sly connected to the Universal Force. We do not find these kind of complex =
situations in the Rama Avatara, at least in the Valmiki Ramayana. Of course=
, if we take the Adhbut Ramayana or such other auxilliary texts and retelli=
ng, we get a different picture. In the Adbhuta Ramayana we have a 1000 head=
ed demon attacking Rama after he kills Ravana, and then Sita turns into Ady=
a Shakti and demolishes the 1000 headed demon and Rama worships her. But if=
 we take only the Ramayana and the Mahabharata,
 the picture that emerges i=
s very clear. Rama is the embodiment of Sattwic mind. Therefore he displays=
 all the great characteristics of satwa, chief of which is self-control, as=
 well as the occasional sadness caused due to separation from his wife Sita=
 whom, at least until Ravana was destroyed, he loved very dearly. Satwa gun=
a creates a true saint, but can also cause some grief when the stability is=
 shaken. Krshna was gunatita. He had no attachment to anything in this worl=
d - man, women, deva, danava, friend, enemy - and therefore he was never af=
fected any trace of negative emotion. His Ananda never left him even in the=
 most trying situations.<br><br>6. Buddha was great spiritual force in this=
 world. But I do not see him fit in the scheme of evolutionary Avatars. His=
 realization, the one he advocated, is a static realization, an end in a vo=
id. This is clearly denying of the reality of this earth. I find this not i=
n tune with what either Rama or Krshna
 espoused. None of them negated this=
 world. If negation of this world and life is the final aim, then why send =
so many avatars at crucial stages of evolutionary development? If the spiri=
tual impact on masses is the reason for Buddha being an Avatara, then why n=
ot Jesus or Zorathrusta.? They are no less impactful in that sense. But do =
they fit in the scheme of spiritual line that these 9 Avataras of Narayana =
indicate in a most logical manner? No. As such many vaishnava traditions in=
 parts of India, do not consider Buddha to be an avatara. Realization, to b=
e complete and holistic, must be both static and dynamic, outside of life a=
s well as inside of life. That is why the Tantras formed their own kind of =
spiritual philosophy, of the world as body of Shakti and therefore an objec=
t of reverence and realization.<br><br>7. The original literature of the Na=
th Yogis used to mention 9 chakras. These are centers of psychological func=
tions. 6 inside the human body
 and 3 too subtle, or non-developed in most =
people, even seekers. It is my belief that each of the 9 Avataras - excludi=
ng Buddha - correspond to the full power and force of one of these 9 Chakra=
s. Similarly, the 9 grahas, or that which can modify consciousness or allow=
 the consciousness to explore and express itself is various possiblities, a=
re 9 in number. The lagna is a reference point and not a graha. Therefore t=
he chief Avatars who represent the parable of evolution are nine in number.=
 And the ninth of the sequence is yet to come.<br><br>8. I cannot comment o=
n which graha would typically represent which Avatara. I know of what the B=
PHS says, however, it is my belief - feel free to disagree with it -:)[one =
cannot rule out some deep-rooted corruption of understanding or textual mis=
representation in this Kali-Yuga] - that the Atmah among the Avataras has n=
ot yet appeared. It will be Kalki, or as Vimalananda seems to say in the Ag=
hora books, Nishkalanka
 - the stainless one. There is only one thing which=
 is perfectly stainless, the Atmah .After a Nirguna/Gunatita awastha comes =
living in the full and complete purity and might and force and strength of =
the Atmah. By the sheer dint of his purity the last Avatara will burn away =
opposing forces of this world and fulfill the purpose of evolution. Even Kr=
shna used diplomacy at various points in his adult life to achieve his ends=
. Kalki, I am speculating, won't even need that. The white horse and that s=
word is a metaphor. He will be the only one capable enough to rectify the v=
arious errors and corruptions that beset our age. <br><br>Well, this is how=
