 and mind. Soul is seen as a representative of god in us, because of some b=
asic attributes of it. It is the higher self and has no agendas, no likes o=
r dislikes.<br> <br>Once mind fancies a separate existence with some a=
gendas/desires, soul supports the individualized consciousness stemming fro=
m that fancy and sees it as its dharma. It lends strength and support to EV=
ERY aspect of this individualized consciousness (e.g. mind, energy, intelle=
ct, learning ability, enjoyment, discipline etc). It supports them fully an=
d yet has no desires/agendas/likes/dislikes of its own! It impassionately w=
itnesses and records all of one's agendas and karmas so that Laws of Nature=
 give proper fruits later
 on. It does all that despite full awareness that=
 it is neither doing those karmas nor receiving the fruits. As mind and oth=
er aspects of the individualized consciousness entertain the notion that th=
ey are doing things and begetting the fruits, soul supports them fully in t=
his play. It sees that as its dharma and does it impassionately.<br> <=
br>Now, does this sound exciting? Perhaps not to all. This functionality of=
 an impassionate witness supporting the play, may not seem interesting enou=
gh to some.<br> <br>On the other hand, mind has likes, dislikes and ag=
endas. It is constantly pursuing those agendas, getting things and achievin=
g things. Movement of mind is what keeps the individualization going!!! Tho=
ugh soul is the support for everything else in the individualized conscious=
ness, soul is a witness doing its dharma impassionately. It is mind that ke=
